  <longtitle>IUPAC Gold Book - ionic strength, I</longtitle>
  <title>ionic strength</title>
  <index>quantity</index>
  <termversion>2.3.3</termversion>
  <lastupdated>2014-02-24</lastupdated>
  <definitions>
    <item>
      <id>1</id>
      <text>On a molality basis, Im = (1/2)∑ mB.zB^2 is the charge number of ion B. The ionic strength on a concentration basis is defined analogously .</text>
      <links>
        <item>
          <title>charge number</title>
          <url>https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/C00993</url>
        </item>
      </links>
      <math>
        <item>
          <meaning>Ionic strength based on molality</meaning>
          <type>equation</type>
          <alttext>Im = (1/2)∑ mB.zB^2</alttext>
          <latex>I_{m}=\frac{1}{2}\ \sum m_{\text{B}}\ z_{\text{B}}^{2}</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <alttext>z B</alttext>
          <latex>z_{\text{B}}</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <alttext>Ic = (1/2)∑ cB.zB^2</alttext>
          <latex>I_{c}=\frac{1}{2}\ \sum c_{\text{B}}\ z_{\text{B}}^{2}</latex>
        </item>
      </math>
      <sources>
        <item>Green Book, 2nd ed., p. 50 (https://goldbook.iupac.org/files/pdf/green_book_2ed.pdf)</item>
        <item>PAC, 1996, 68, 957. 'Glossary of terms in quantities and units in Clinical Chemistry (IUPAC-IFCC Recommendations 1996)' on page 977 (https://doi.org/10.1351/pac199668040957)</item>
      </sources>
    </item>
  </definitions>
